nomy, and also the overall political economy of the system they help in creating. Several key questions are raised, including when and why do some conflicts protract, and what types of socioeconomic and political configurations make peaceful resolutions difficult to obtain? Also addressed are the lessons of other protracted conflicts, such as those found in Lebanon, Angola, and Italy. In this expanded second edition Richani contributes new chapters looking at developments in Colombia since the book's initial publication a decade ago and a look at the challenges for peace that lie ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aColombia -- Economic conditions -- 1970-. 0aColombia -- Politics and government -- 1974-. 0aColombia -- Social conditions. 0aViolence -- Colombia. 0aViolence -- Economic aspects -- Colombia. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Conflict Resolution. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aRosenau, James N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438446950423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438446950/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles